*************************** T H E O R Y **************************2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
TALYS is a computer code system for the prediction and analysis   2034 1451
of nuclear reactions. TALYS simulates reactions that involve      2034 1451
neutrons, gamma-rays, protons, deuterons, tritons, helions and    2034 1451
alpha-particles, in the 1 keV - 200 MeV energy range and for      2034 1451
target nuclides of mass 12 and heavier. This is achieved by       2034 1451
implementing a suite of nuclear reaction models into a single     2034 1451
code system. It enables to evaluate nuclear reactions from        2034 1451
the unresolved resonance region up to intermediate energies. This 2034 1451
evaluation is based on a theoretical analysis that utilizes the   2034 1451
optical model, compound nucleus statistical theory, direct        2034 1451
reactions and pre-equilibrium processes, in combination with      2034 1451
databases and models for nuclear structure. For Ca-43, the        2034 1451
following output of TALYS is stored in this data file:            2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
- Total, elastic and non-elastic cross sections                   2034 1451
- Elastic scattering angular distributions                        2034 1451
- Inelastic cross sections to discrete states                     2034 1451
- Inelastic scattering angular distributions to discrete states   2034 1451
- Exclusive channel cross sections, e.g. (n,g), (n,2n), (n,np),.. 2034 1451
- Exclusive channel energy spectra                                2034 1451
- Exclusive channel double-differential spectra                   2034 1451
- Exclusive gamma production for discrete states and continuum    2034 1451
- Isomeric and ground state cross sections                        2034 1451
- Residual production cross sections                              2034 1451
- Total particle cross sections, e.g. (n,xn), (n,xp),..           2034 1451
- Total particle energy spectra                                   2034 1451
- Total particle double-differential spectra                      2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
Here follows a short description of the used nuclear models:      2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
##### OPTICAL MODEL                                               2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
All optical model calculations are performed by ECIS-97 [ray94],  2034 1451
in TALYS used as a subroutine. The default optical model          2034 1451
potentials (OMP) used are the local and global parameterizations  2034 1451
of Koning and Delaroche [kon03]. These are phenomenological OMPs  2034 1451
for neutrons and protons which in principle are valid over the    2034 1451
1 keV - 200 MeV energy range, though the low energy boundary of   2034 1451
validity may differ from nucleus to nucleus (e.g. for the total   2034 1451
cross sections, experimental data are included directly in the    2034 1451
file for energies below that boundary). Solving the Schroedinger  2034 1451
equation with this OMP yields the total cross section, the        2034 1451
shape-elastic cross section, the shape-elastic angular            2034 1451
distribution, the wave functions for the direct reaction cross    2034 1451
sections (see below), the transmission coefficients for the       2034 1451
compound nucleus model (see below) and the reaction cross         2034 1451
sections for the pre-equilibrium model (see below).               2034 1451
For neutrons and protons, the used parameterization is given in   2034 1451
Eq. (7) of [kon03].                                               2034 1451
To calculate the transmission coefficients and reaction cross     2034 1451
sections for deuterons, tritons, helions and alpha particles, we  2034 1451
use OMPs that are directly derived from our nucleon potentials    2034 1451
using Watanabe's folding approach [mad88].                        2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
##### DIRECT REACTIONS                                            2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
The built-in ECIS-97 is used for coupled-channels or DWBA         2034 1451
calculations for rotational or vibrational (or a combination of   2034 1451
these) nuclides. For Ca-43, DWBA was used to compute the direct   2034 1451
cross sections to several low-lying discrete levels of the        2034 1451
even-even core Ca-42. The weak-coupling model was then used       2034 1451
to spread the collective strength over the odd levels of Ca-43.   2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
In addition, a macroscopic, phenomenological model to describe    2034 1451
giant resonances in the inelastic channel is used. For each       2034 1451
multipolarity an energy weighted sum rule applies and a DWBA      2034 1451
calculation with ECIS-97 is performed for each giant resonance    2034 1451
state. The cross section is then spread over the continuum with a 2034 1451
Gaussian distribution.                                            2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
##### COMPOUND NUCLEUS                                            2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
For binary compound nucleus reactions we use the model of         2034 1451
Moldauer [mol80], i.e. the Hauser-Feshbach model [hau52]          2034 1451
corrected for width fluctuations. The transmission coefficients   2034 1451
have been generated with the aforementioned OMPs and the full     2034 1451
j,l-dependence of the transmission coefficients in the            2034 1451
Hauser-Feshbach model is used. For each nucleus that can be       2034 1451
reached through a binary reaction, several discrete levels and a  2034 1451
continuum described by level densities are included               2034 1451
simultaneously as competing channels.                             2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
The compound nucleus angular distributions are calculated with    2034 1451
the Blatt-Biedenharn formalism [bla52], leading to compound       2034 1451
nucleus Legendre coefficients that are added to their direct      2034 1451
counterparts. For multiple compound emission, i.e. emitted        2034 1451
particles after the binary emission, we use the Hauser-Feshbach   2034 1451
model. Again, for each residual nucleus several discrete states   2034 1451
are included as well as a continuum described by level densities. 2034 1451
Multiple compound emission is continued until all reaction        2034 1451
channels are closed and the population distribution of all        2034 1451
residual nuclides is depleted, through gamma decay, until they    2034 1451
end up in the ground state or in an isomer.                       2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
For the level density, we take the composite formula proposed by  2034 1451
Gilbert and Cameron [gil65], consisting of a constant temperature 2034 1451
law at low energies and a Fermi gas expression at high energies.  2034 1451
For the level density parameter a we use the energy dependent     2034 1451
expression proposed by Ignatyuk [ign75] to take into account the  2034 1451
damping of shell effects at high excitation energy. We have       2034 1451
obtained the parameters for the Ignatyuk formula from a           2034 1451
simultaneous fit to all experimental D_0 values as present in the 2034 1451
RIPL library. If necessary, we adjust individual parameters to    2034 1451
obtain a better fit to experiment.                                2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
Gamma-ray transmission coefficients are generated with the        2034 1451
Kopecky-Uhl generalized Lorentzian for strength                   2034 1451
functions [kop90], with giant dipole resonance parameters taken   2034 1451
from the RIPL library [rip98], and normalized with experimental   2034 1451
radiative widths [gar84].                                         2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
##### PRE-EQUILIBRIUM REACTIONS                                   2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
For pre-equilibrium reactions, which become important for         2034 1451
incident energies above about 10 MeV, we use the two-component    2034 1451
exciton model [kon04b], in which the neutron or proton types of   2034 1451
particles and holes are followed throughout the reaction. For     2034 1451
energies above 20 MeV, multiple pre-equilibrium emission up to    2034 1451
any order of particle emission was included in the calculations.  2034 1451
A parameterization for the squared matrix element is used that is 2034 1451
valid for the whole energy range of this evaluation.              2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
For deuterons, tritons, helions and alpha-particles, an extra     2034 1451
contribution was added from the pick/up and knock-out reaction    2034 1451
model by Kalbach [kal01].                                         2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
For photons, the model of Akkermans and Gruppelaar [akk85] was    2034 1451
applied, to simulate the direct and semi-direct capture           2034 1451
processes.                                                        2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
The angular distribution systematics by Kalbach [kal88] were used 2034 1451
to describe the angular distributions for all continuum           2034 1451
particles. An isotopic distribution for photons was adopted.      2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
****** C O M P A R I S O N    W I T H    E X P E R I M E N T *****2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
This evaluation was performed simultaneously with other adjacent  2034 1451
isotopes, both for incident neutrons and protons. This enables,   2034 1451
when compared with a single-isotope effort, to put stronger       2034 1451
constraints on the produced calculated data, i.e. a globally      2034 1451
good comparison between TALYS and experimental data is requested  2034 1451
for all isotopes at the same time, while nucleus-specific input   2034 1451
(default or adjusted) parameters are consistently used for all    2034 1451
isotopes. Also, experimental data that is not available for the   2034 1451
isotope under study may be present, and tested, for adjacent      2034 1451
nuclides or for other projectiles. If these can be successfully   2034 1451
described by the models, a similar performance can be expected    2034 1451
for the present data file.                                        2034 1451
A few level density parameters for residual nuclides have been    2034 1451
adjusted to enforce agreement with the experimental data. The     2034 1451
changes in the level density parameters, a, were all kept within  2034 1451
10% of their default values.                                      2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
##### TOTAL AND REACTION CROSS SECTIONS AND ELASTIC SCATTERING    2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
The spherical OMP was tested against experimental data for total  2034 1451
cross sections and elastic scattering angular distributions.      2034 1451
Consult [kon03] for the complete experimental database and for a  2034 1451
comparison of calculations and measurements over the whole energy 2034 1451
range for natural Ca.                                             2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
##### OTHER PARTIAL CROSS SECTIONS                                2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
- (n,gamma):                                                      2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
The calculated capture cross section is renormalized, by          2034 1451
overruling the default renormalization to the s-wave strength     2034 1451
function, to the available experimental data, all taken from the  2034 1451
EXFOR database. A normalization factor of 0.80 was used. The      2034 1451
pre-equilibrium gamma cross section was adjusted to the data by   2034 1451
multiplying the calculated result by a factor of 3.0.             2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
- (n,p):                                                          2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
Many experimental (n,p) cross sections are available from EXFOR.  2034 1451
These have been used as validation for our TALYS calculation.     2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
##### PARTICLE SPECTRA                                            2034 1451
                                                                  2034 1451
For Ca-43, an adjustment of the default matrix element            2034 1451
parameterization of [kon04b] for pre-equilibrium reactions of a   2034 1451
factor of 0.7 was needed, to describe the aforementioned cross    2034 1451
sections and emission spectra for nuclides in this mass range.    2034 1451
For high-energy neutron and charged particle spectra, the average 2034 1451
quality is also determined by the pre-equilibrium model and its   2034 1451
global parameterization. No high-energy experiments are           2034 1451
available, though neutron induced reaction spectra between 28 and 2034 1451
63 MeV on Al [ben02], Si [ben02b] and Fe [sly03] have enabled us  2034 1451
to better constrain the results, through the aforementioned       2034 1451
matrix element, for particle yields and double-differential       2034 1451
spectra for all ejectiles up to alpha particles.                  2034 1451
